{
  "doc_id": "36207",
  "text": "Cytokinins can be classified into 4 groups [isopentenyladenine (iP)-type, tZ-type, cis-zeatin-type, and aromatic cytokinins] depending on the structure of the side chain. Biologically important cytokinins are iP-type and tZ-type cytokinins, and the first steps of their biosynthesis are catalyzed by ATP/ADP isopentenyltransferases (ATP/ADP IPTs) (in Arabidopsis, AtIPT1, AtIPT3, AtIPT4, AtIPT5, AtIPT6, AtIPT7, and AtIPT8) [CITATION_1] . The AtIPT3, AtIPT5, and AtIPT7 genes are most highly expressed among genes for ATP/ADP IPTs in Arabidopsis [CITATION_2] . The atipt3;5;7 triple and atipt1;3;5;7 quadruple mutants have severely decreased levels of iP-type and tZ-type cytokinins, and their overall growth is severely affected [CITATION_3] . The tZ-type cytokinins are formed from isopentenyladenine ribose phosphate by hydroxylation of the side chain by cytochrome P450 monooxygenases [CITATION_4] . cis-zeatin-type cytokinins are produced from isopentenylated tRNAs (15), but they play only a minor role in the growth of most plants. The biosynthesis and role of aromatic cytokinins are not well known.",
